abstract: Fisk sells Scandinavian-style seafood at its homey store on Delancey Street.
snippet: Fisk sells Scandinavian-style seafood at its homey store on Delancey Street.
lead_paragraph: This homey little storefront’s name, Fisk, means fish in Swedish. That’s almost all you need to know. Annika Sundvik, above, who owns it with her husband, John Lavelle, sells all sorts of fish and seafood, fresh and cured, and almost all in Scandinavian style. Tiny smoked Norwegian shrimp, homemade gravlax, peppered mackerel, smoked herring, pickled baby octopus and several roes, including lumpfish, wasabi and seaweed, are listed on a blackboard, along with fresh seafood like cod and lobster. Some cheeses, including Vasterbotten; produce like potatoes, beets, cabbage and onions; and pantry products, like lingonberry cordials and packaged flatbreads, are also sold. The couple, who own White Slab Palace, a restaurant and bar next door, are gradually adding prepared foods, like smorrebrod (open-faced sandwiches).

abstract: There was no cataclysm that defined the summer, but the average temperature, 77.8 degrees, was a record.
snippet: There was no cataclysm that defined the summer, but the average temperature, 77.8 degrees, was a record.
lead_paragraph: With one final, fitting blast of 96-degree heat on Tuesday, the summer of 2010 went down in the National Weather Service’s record books as the hottest ever in New York City.
